-Z9gJZTFnLWY0wngKVH5OWZIj2p9Afzgprcb_07XZswFus2_h3R-SqULAcFnRaYz5oekahL2SQRVdJ7MvKzE_uAIN_AZjGwETnTv6OLbPV02QlLJPm91UC65IQ8IFFDG1N5zXUC7pG70MMckkC19IASHd7GraszR-B0y71Z8eBWgd7GDysia7a5sha4-0r8lK4hGmet90Hmvq--rLeQTrE7FJtC9rvTTbKp2zV98-iCLJlappwPDhidklUe2je3DaADet5EKDYJDXMWH5GRYkMdd7gg7Bj8cW9y1s78XWArb55tl64WsRg-6erwaLfubK0ruyZ0FtHvKAW6SXfdFTNG7GqZ1l474zd7Il-ZaDOF0UwWcjkV18jJqwHpTjxt_sEnAAUKd_c3xoUoEcA3jOmK8bqwoVLjOURymJhz4tkRXtNPI36BLlA_TY5zGDulKMXfX5Nmn2N9lRx-TP_iukajdMxA-3LFLFxyr61hrxDi1XTF2sO-ZyuiQmid72dS2GhD-GkbQiZWW3D4M7o2_-RqUVnmRpN4yfY38LfbrWxS1E4VPe3kDg_2UOA42nuDLI6_pFILMCv2aHHT-VJFFUhTcRHebGoV5r5DjSuE5hydi9AtXdQyp0EL1yyYEdeajKSVM35UOwo3BpIXpVbNivM1IDBkSa7uJzTS5pN5sgKE1QpyGXsIYXoa83EX76E14fohD9yQfjsUR0UlPXPtkRCM8u4dLeh3E7hBSH9LycVuCa3HMVzRfXYLAEBYB1OYJ6-5IGkE-JJQTTqSKdVzYCiNhXx-jd1c5na09e7Lx0bRdS71RaL4XUuajqCLk_fKfLkNA5S1d4YtwElfdSYFuVBmnGWwxl2nHwoqO7v6m4RYna2pSnWagpzvIbuvxYZHVTOmxOWC2miQW1ur0FFE9z7GFq8AVxO0GnOJvyLGUmkCatEbMkFpKWjn6ZwsSYDYuaxWLdjQfqQH7LiKJMB8wMJjw5PFmzQhpx_SdHilEbHji1OHmVdbeYbV_248iw==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering proto2 message definitions**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how to define a proto2 message with an extension range and extension. I know I’ll need to use FileDescriptor.buildFrom to set it up correctly. Additionally, I need to find the extension field using findExtensionByName to ensure everything is working as intended. There’s a lot to keep in mind, but I’m focused on getting it all right!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Java file structure**\\n\\nIn Java, a file can only have one public top-level class. If I need a public descriptor outer, it might require a separate file, which seems like a mapping violation. I wonder if a helper file would work here. The rule specifies a one-to-one relationship between report classes and generated test class files. I could potentially place a public static nested DescriptorOuter inside the public test, but then the binary name would contain a